SYMP:0019151.def: A respiratory system and chest symptom that is characterized by an abnormal accumulation of fluid in the lungs.

name: diaphoresis
diaphoresis
SYMP:0019152.def: A sweat that is characterized by excessive sweating commonly associated with shock and other medical emergency conditions.

name: dyspnea
dyspnea
SYMP:0019153.def: A respiratory abnormality that is characterized by difficult or labored respiration.

name: hemorrhagic mediastinitis
hemorrhagic mediastinitis
SYMP:0019154.def: A respiratory abnormality that is characterized by inflammation of the mediastinum (the chest cavity, which contains the heart, the thymus gland, some lymph nodes, and parts of the esophagus, aorta, thyroid, and parathyroid glands) as the result of bleeding.

name: eschar
eschar
SYMP:0019158.def: A skin and integumentary tissue symptom that is characterized by a scab formed especially after a burn.

name: boil
boil
SYMP:0019160.def: A skin and integumentary tissue symptom that is characterized by a localized swelling and inflammation of the skin resulting from usually bacterial infection of a hair follicle and adjacent tissue, having a hard central core, and forming pus.

name: muscle pain
muscle pain
SYMP:0019161.def: A pain that is characterized by a pain in one or more muscles.

name: pustule
pustule
SYMP:0019167.def: A skin and integumentary tissue symptom that is characterized by a small circumscribed elevation of the skin containing pus and having an inflamed base.

name: obsolete pneumonia
obsolete pneumonia
SYMP:0019168.def: A pneumonitis that is characterized by an inflammatory illness of the lung resulting from a variety of causes including infection with bacteria, viruses, fungi, or parasites, and chemical or physical injury to the lungs. Its cause may also be officially described as idiopathic, that is, unknown, when infectious causes have been excluded.

name: arthritis
arthritis
SYMP:0019169.def: Arthritis is a musculoskeletal system symptom characterized as an inflammation of joints due to infectious, metabolic, or constitutional causes.

name: spondylitis
spondylitis
SYMP:0019171.def: A nervous system symptom that is characterized by an inflammation of the vertebrae.

name: meningitis
meningitis
SYMP:0019173.def: A nervous system symptom that is characterized by an inflammation of the meninges and especially of the pia mater and the arachnoid.

name: sweaty
sweaty
SYMP:0019175.def: A skin and integumentary tissue symptom that is characterized by the excretion of moisture in visible quantities through the opening of the sweat glands.

name: malaise
malaise
SYMP:0019176.def: A neurological and physiological symptom that is characterized by an indefinite feeling of debility or lack of health, often indicative of or accompanying the onset of an illness.

name: fatigue
fatigue
SYMP:0019177.def: A neurological and physiological symptom that is characterized by a weariness or exhaustion from labor, exertion, or stress.

name: necrotic lesion
necrotic lesion
SYMP:0019178.def: A skin and integumentary tissue symptom that is characterized by regions of cell death to living tissue in an organ, which has suffered damage through injury or disease, such as a wound, ulcer, abscess, or tumor.

name: lightheadedness
lightheadedness
SYMP:0019179.def: A  balance symptom that is characterized by a condition of being dizzy or on the verge of fainting, particularly when one arises to a standing position. Lightheadedness is a predictable consequence of any medication tending to lower blood pressure.

name: constipation
constipation
SYMP:0019180.def: Constipation is a feces and droppings symptom involving the abnormally delayed or infrequent passage of dry hardened feces. Constipation may be categorized into three subtypes: normal-transit, slow-transit, and pelvic floor dysfunction.

name: behavioral symptom
behavioral symptom
SYMP:0019182.def: A nervous system symptom that is characterized by an involvement, or relation to, or emphasizes behavior.

name: hyperactivity
hyperactivity
SYMP:0019183.def: A behavioral symptom that is characterized by an increase in movement, impulsive actions, a shorter attention span, and being easily distracted.

name: limited attention
limited attention
SYMP:0019184.def: A behavioral symptom that is characterized by a restricted rate of information processing by the brain.

name: communication difficulty
communication difficulty
SYMP:0019185.def: A behavioral symptom that is characterized by speech, language and communication needs or communication disabilities.

name: obsessive interests
obsessive interest
SYMP:0019186.def: A behavioral symptom that is characterized by obsessive and highly-focused interests.

name: repetitive behavior
repetitive behavior
SYMP:0019187.def: A behavioral symptom that is characterized by an unusual repetitive motor movements or manipulation of objects.

name: intracranial hemorrhage
intracranial hemorrhage
SYMP:0019188.def: A hemorrhage that is characterized by any bleeding occurring within the skull.

name: intracerebral hemorrhage
intracerebral hemorrhage
SYMP:0019189.def: A hemorrhage that is characterized by bleeding within the brain tissue itself.

name: subdural hemorrhage
subdural hemorrhage
SYMP:0019190.def: A hemorrhage that is characterized by bleeding that occurs within the skull of head but outside the actual brain tissue.

name: airway stenosis
airway stenosis
SYMP:0020000.def: A respiratory system and chest symptom that is characterized by a narrowing in the airway that obstructs the passage of air into the lungs.  Examples include tracheal and laryngotracheal stenosis.

name: apthous ulcer
apthous ulcer
SYMP:0020001.def: A skin ulcer that is characterized by a small recurrent, painful, round or ovoid ulcers with well-defined erythematous margins, like a halo, and a central yellow or gray floor found in the soft tissue of the oral cavity.

name: ageusia
ageusia
SYMP:0020004.def: A disturbances of sensation of smell and taste that is characterized by a complete loss of taste function of the tongue.

name: agitation
agitation
SYMP:0020006.def: A neurological and physiological symptom that is characterized by a feeling of irritability or severe restlessness.

name: barking croup cough
bark croup cough
SYMP:0020008.def: A cough that is characterized by a tight, low-pitched, and barky (like a barking seal) cough.

name: abnormal weight loss
abnormal weight loss
SYMP:0020013.def: A weight loss that is characterized as deviating from what is normal or usual, typically in a way that is undesirable or worrying.

name: chronic weight loss
chronic weight loss
SYMP:0020014.def: A weight loss that is characterized by conditions that last 1 year or more and require ongoing medical attention, or limit activities of daily living, or both.

name: acute weight gain
acute weight gain
SYMP:0020016.def: A weight gain that is characterized by a severe and sudden onset.

name: chronic weight gain
chronic weight gain
SYMP:0020017.def: A weight gain that is characterized by conditions that last 1 year or more and require ongoing medical attention, or limit activities of daily living, or both.

name: overweight
overweight
SYMP:0020018.def: A weight symptom that is characterized by being too heavy for one’s height. Excess body weight can come from fat, muscle, bone, and/or water retention. Being overweight does not always mean being obese.

name: postnasal drainage
postnasal drainage
SYMP:0020019.def: A nose symptom that is characterized by an an excessive secretion of mucous down the back of the throat.

name: bone conduction hyperacusis
bone conduction hyperacusis
SYMP:0020022.def: An ear symptom - need proper definition - placeholder for xref.

name: bronchospasm
bronchospasm
SYMP:0020024.def: A respiratory system and chest symptom that is characterized by constriction of the air passages of the lung (as in asthma) by spasmodic contraction of the bronchial muscles.

name: caseation
caseation
SYMP:0020025.def: A respiratory system and chest symptom that is characterized by necrosis of tissue with conversion of damaged tissue into a soft cheesy substance.

name: wet cough
wet cough
SYMP:0020027.def: A cough that is characterized by a production and expectoration (bringing up) of mucus (phlegm) or sputum.

name: concentration difficulty
concentration difficulty
SYMP:0020029.def: An alteration of consciousness that is characterized by a decreased ability to focus one's thoughts on something. Concentration difficulties can be related to difficulty staying awake, impulsiveness, intrusive thoughts or concerns, overactivity, or inattention. They can be caused by medical, cognitive or psychological problems, or, may be related to sleep disorders, medications, alcohol, or drugs.

name: patches of hair loss with a black dot pattern
patch of hair loss with a black dot pattern
SYMP:0020030.def: A hair symptom that is characterized by patchy hair loss and the presence of comedo-like cadaver hairs, which appear as black dots.

name: chest discomfort
chest discomfort
SYMP:0020031.def: A respiratory system and chest symptom that is characterized by pain, pressure, tightness, or other discomfort originating in or radiating to the chest, which constitutes an important indicator of potentially serious cardiac or cardiovascular disorders.

name: chest tightness
chest tightness
SYMP:0020032.def: A chest discomfort that is characterized by any type of pain or discomfort between your upper belly and lower neck.

name: paroxysmal cough
paroxysmal cough
SYMP:0020033.def: A cough that is characterized by a persistent cough with sudden onset due to difficulty expelling thick mucus from the tracheobronchial tree. This type of cough is associated with diseases such as Pertussis (Whooping Cough).

name: conjunctival congestion
conjunctival congestion
SYMP:0020035.def: An eye symptom that is characterized by (need def conjunctival congestion - placeholder for xref).

name: conjunctival suffusion
conjunctival suffusion
SYMP:0020037.def: An eye symptom that is characterized by (need def conjunctival suffusion - placeholder for xref).

name: contracture
contracture
SYMP:0020039.def: A musculoskeletal system symptom that is characterized by a permanent tightening of the muscles, tendons, skin, and nearby tissues that causes the joints to shorten and become very stiff.

name: corkscrew hair
corkscrew hair
SYMP:0020041.def: A hair symptom that is characterized by coiled “corkscrew” hairs on the surface of the arms, legs and chest, which can occur as a result low level of ascorbic acid (vitamin C).

name: corneal scarring
corneal scar
SYMP:0020042.def: A cornea symptom that is characterized by scarring (an opacity or irregularity in the cornea) of the cornea, from trauma; abrasion; bacterial, fungal, viral, or parasitic infection; or disease, and can result in impaired vision, or even blindness.

name: dark urine
dark urine
SYMP:0020043.def: A urinary system symptom that is characterized by an elevation in the concentration of the the pigments from foods, dyes, and medications in urine. The dilution of these pigment is dependent on the amount of water intake and severe dehydration can lead to a dark color.

name: hair shedding
hair shed
SYMP:0020044.def: A hair symptom that is characterized by significant falling out of hair, which may be a result of stress, high fever, and other factors.

name: balance symptom
balance symptom
SYMP:0020045.def: A neurological and physiological symptom that is characterized by any of the following: dizziness or vertigo (a spinning sensation); falling or feeling as if you are going to fall; staggering when walking; lightheadedness, faintness, or a floating sensation; and confusion or disorientation.

name: feeding problem
feeding problem
SYMP:0020046.def: A feeding difficulties and mismanagement that is characterized by delays and/or disorders in the development of eating and drinking skills including disordered placement of food in the mouth, difficulty in appropriately manipulating food when it is in the mouth, difficulty chewing, and/or difficulty swallowing.

name: descending muscle paralysis
descend muscle paralysis
SYMP:0020047.def: A paralysis that is characterized by a loss of motor function in one or more muscles, which can also be accompanied by a loss of feeling (sensory loss). Descending paralysis contrasts with ascending paralysis in that descending paralysis presents in the upper limbs before the lower limbs. Descending paralysis occurs in conditions such as botulism.

name: delayed psychomotor development
delay psychomotor development
SYMP:0020049.def: A nutrition, metabolism, and development symptom that is characterized by the delay in development child's cognitive, emotional, motor, and social capacities from the beginning of life throughout fetal and neonatal periods, infancy, childhood, and adolescence.

name: decreased tearing
decrease tearing
SYMP:0020050.def: An eye symptom that is characterized by a reduction in the saline fluid secreted by the lacrimal gland.

name: decreased metabolism
decrease metabolism
SYMP:0020051.def: A nutrition, metabolism, and development symptom that is characterized by a reduction in the chemical reactions catalyzed by enzymes, which keep us alive. Metabolism allows organisms to grow, reproduce, maintain their structures, and respond to their environments and can be divided into catabolism (breaking down of organic matter) and anabolism (building of molecules).

name: hand weakness
hand weakness
SYMP:0020052.def: A muscle weakness that is characterized by a reduction in muscle strength, which may be the result of a variety of conditions, such as carpal tunnel syndrome, arthritis, peripheral neuropathy, tendon damage, and ganglion cysts.

name: mammary gland inflammation
mammary gland inflammation
SYMP:0020053.def: A skin and integumentary tissue symptom that is characterized by an inflammation of the mammary gland or udder and usually caused by infection.

name: severe mammary gland inflammation
severe mammary gland inflammation
SYMP:0020054.def: A mammary gland inflammation that is characterized by an increased intensity or severity of the condition.

name: cerebrovascular accident
cerebrovascular accident
SYMP:0020056.def: A nervous system symptom that is characterized by a loss of blood flow to part of the brain, which damages brain tissue. Cerebrovascular accidents are caused by blood clots and broken blood vessels in the brain.

name: bronchiole inflammation
bronchiole inflammation
SYMP:0020057.def: A respiratory system and chest symptom that is characterized by acute inflammation of the bronchi, accompanied by inflamed patches in the nearby lobules of the lungs.

name: outlet dysfunction constipation
outlet dysfunction constipation
SYMP:0020061.def: A constipation that is characterized by difficulty passing bowel movements after they reach the rectum. One experiences difficulty evacuating the stool and often has to strain or press the fingers into the vagina or in front of or into the rectum to help remove the stool. Outlet dysfunction can be caused by inappropriate or abnormal muscle contraction of the pelvic floor (called pelvic floor dyssynergia or dyssynergic defecation) which can respond to biofeedback. It may also be due to a rectocele or other structural changes in the pelvic floor that will require medical or at times, surgical treatment.

name: soft tissue necrosis
soft tissue necrosis
SYMP:0020062.def: A musculoskeletal system symptom that is characterized by necrosis (i.e. tissue death) of soft tissue, including muscle, fat, blood vessels, nerves, tendons, and tissues that surround the bones and joints.
